-- Oil Options Volatility Rises as Underlying Futures Advance
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-05-06T20:09:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-06/oil-options-volatility-rises-as-underlying-futures-advance.html
Crude options volatility rose as
underlying futures touched a one-month high in intraday trading.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 23.63 percent at 3:50 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , up from 22.49 percent on May 3.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery rose 55
cents to settle at $96.16 a barrel on the Nymex. Futures gained
as much as $1.56 to $97.17, the highest intraday level since
April 2.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
July $90 puts, which rose 8 cents to $1.16 a barrel on volume of
11,081 contracts at 3:48 p.m. June $96 calls were the second-
most active, dropping 5 cents to $1.37 on volume of 2,711 lots.  Puts accounted for 55 percent of electronic trading volume
today. Bearish bets on May 3 made up 54 percent of the dayâ€™s
volume of 221,855 contracts.  June $100 calls were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 13,562 contracts changing hands. They
rose 15 cents to 27 cents a barrel. June $98 calls increased 38
cents to 66 cents a barrel on 12,794 lots.  Open interest was highest for June $80 puts with 41,337
contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 38,118 and
December $110 calls with 34,289.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-
outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
